tweets.text: Yes, #Relay 2 is coming! Here's a nice talk by @wincent https://t.co/9Y4lfye3sO
#Relay 2 development seems to be driven mostly by mobile app requirements. Not sure how noticeable is the speedup on desktop.
But what I love about #Relay 2 is the revised mutations! I hate writing mutations in Relay 1, I have big hopes now!
Another improvement of #Relay 2 is more readable requests. The Chrome Relay inspector is currently unusable, imho, because of that.
As for client-fields in #Relay 2, I'm curious to try and see if they're enough to replace Redux, which is what I use now for client state.

My rule of thumb for dependency management and DIP: for any external library, never have import statements in more than ONE internal module.
... not even logging. Very very few exceptions, like React. You can't pretend you're not married to that.

tweets.text: Logging is pervasive. Every function carries around a "logger" instance, which is instrumented to add extra info, as a json obj.
Our logging idea is very similar to https://t.co/dlBSpGLhJ5. But we don't let the library objects leak into the code, but use a wrapper.
We stream every log line (a json obj) to @logmatic, which is *awesome* to analyze and produce metrics.
Every server-side request has a unique id that's added to the log lines, so it possible to rebuild the entire history of a given request.
Every sanity check that fails produces a special "security warning" log event. A real time alert notifies hack attempts.

#CSSmodules bring great DX. They solve the shortcomings of inline styles using familiar CSS. https://t.co/KcEfdyFKjN
But #CSSmodules are a world of its own, you either embrace them, or fight them. Because of less specificity, they collide with global css.
For a greenfield project, I have no doubt, #CSSMmodules is the way to go. But everyone on the team must be equally convinced.
When we started #CSSmodules didn't exist, so we have a mixture of techniques which makes it hard sometimes to get proper styling to work.
They're similar to UUIDs. I store them in the logger instance that's passed around the functions as a parameter. They don't appear in http.

We use @goconvox to deploy our #Docker based app. An effective way to leverage the AWS infrastructure without going insane.
